description.text:
Update - I made Many Formicarums 2 at the link.
It has a different styles of water grids and more

        *Sorry for the long description, I might also fix this sometime.*

       !!!!The files not in zips are just for pictures, they are duplicates!!!!

I've made a bunch of smaller formicarums out of chopped up pieces of the design from Triplicator. I made these mainly because i wanted the top to not cover the cotton, for easy changing and watering but i got carried away and made all these. Some of these may be a bit small for some people, but i don't have any big colony's yet, and i like to be able to take sections off if they get too much garbage or get mold or something. All the information is below

Test Grid - All of these use a small grid instead of the holes in the original designs. It seems to work better for me. Does anyone like the holes better? Everyone should be able to print this but you can test it with this.

Small Chamber V2 - The top is the same size as small chamber cross. Also there is a top for the water hole. Not sure how useful it is but i included it for all chambers.

Small Chamber Cross V2 - A Cross Section. The arrangement of male and female seems to work best for me. maybe i'll make another in the future?

Large Chamber V3 - The openings are straight across long ways. The top is the same size as V4 and V5.

Large Chamber V4 - The openings are straight across short ways only on one side.

Large Chamber V5 - Same as V4 but with a third opening on the long way. The green ones in the pictures.

Xl Chamber - My version of Dantius's remix. My verison has smaller walls, a flat floor and several other improvements. I meant to make it the same size, but i ended up making it 2 mm bigger on the inside. I may fix it in the future, but this is it for now.
V1H - the only one with the heating cable slot
V2 - has a third opening on the bottom. M for male, F for female.
V3 - has two openings on the bottom. 2 male or 2 female. It should work well with
cross sections.

Note - All of the tops may need a bit of sanding to fit right,

Tube Adaptors - I may move these at a later time, but for now they are part of this. these are for 3/8 tubing(I said 1/4 inch before, I was wrong). There are also some end stops with vents if anyone wants them. Sorry there is so much in this one post, but at least i posted it.

Extras - Make you own Formicarum! I included the cut up pieces and blank chambers so you can make your own design. The files are all in Microsoft's 3d builder. It might not be the best program, but it's real easy to use, and can import stl's. You could also export them as obj if you want to use something else.

I also have tube connectors and tube extras at the links

description.text:
I needed a very small tripod to hold my Logitech c920 pointing at my printer. I've been propping it up using a failed print, but that's not the most stable platform. (See "Before.jpg")

Other tripods are far more involved than I needed - I don't need the tripod to adjust, I don't need it to be big, I just need it to keep a solid base and screw in. I also don't want to get a handful of hardware just to do this.

So I made a design that has a very short base, a reasonably small footprint, overhangs less than 45 degrees, and only takes minimal hardware. A single 1/4-20 hex head bolt slots in from the bottom, and a single 1/4-20 nut to lock it on. Then the camera screws onto the bolt. Simple and done.

Please don't use this for any large cameras, because I don't want any dead DSLRs haunting me. This is a targeted solution at a webcam.

Notes:

I'd do 3 perimeters or more for strength. More top surfaces with less infill, etc.

The overhangs are pretty gradual, so no supports needed. Print it top down, legs up (as it should load) and it's pretty simple and straight forward.

0.3mm tolerance is built into the part, but if your printer is more finicky you can scale it up in the X and Y to make it more tolerant. Worst case, bore out the center hole with a drill the size of the bolt you want to use, and use a washer to cover the bolt head slot.

Scaling it up to fit a 3/8" bolt would significantly oversize the space for the bolt's head. If someone would like a 3/8" version leave me a comment and I'll slap one together, but I'm going to work under the assumption that anyone using a tripod this chintzy is not using the kind of commercial camera equipment that uses a 3/8. I'm also pretty sure this won't be a wide enough base to support a camera that large.

I'm printing with a 0.6mm nozzle right now and I don't have it dialed in perfectly, so I'm pretty egregiously over-extruding. The bolt slid through fine, but the head was too snug to push in. I used a washer and a nut with a wrench to pull the bolt head into the slot, then once seated I removed the washer. At this point it's so tight I don't need the bolt on top to keep it in place, but I am leaving it there anyway just so I don't have to worry about it ever getting loose. Even with the nut I have about .4" or 10mm of unused thread from a 1" bolt, so 1" is more than enough even if you want to do something weird.

I also printed it with 35% infill because I was too lazy to change my settings. We're talking about <1 cent and under a minute of printing difference, so unimportant to say the least.

If it were wobbly I would consider getting a 3/4" or possibly a 1/2" long bolt (or cutting the 1" down to size), but the extra bit doesn't affect the stability in the least. When I tap the camera it wobbles based on its internal adjustments, and the tripod itself remains exactly where it was. If you are putting it somewhere that vibrates a lot you might consider putting on some plastidip or those little rubber feet for furniture, but probably if these an issue for you, a different design is probably better.

Because of the USB cord I screwed the tripod onto the camera rather than the camera onto the tripod. I would assume everyone would come upon this solution on their own, but I'm a System Administrator, so I have seen the many and varied ways people can fail to come up with what seems like an obvious solution.

Step 1: Camera slips one too many times

Have your webcam slide off a failed statue print one more time while you are trying to stream a print for a friend.
Optional step 1a: Curse a little under your breath.
Optional step 1a alternative: Curse a lot, not under your breath.

Step 2: Fail to find something perfect

Find lots and lots of tripods, all of which require a handful of screws and nuts to assemble, or else are a dozen parts, all to allow for tons of options, almost all of which are unneeded for this very specific and focused purpose.

Step 3: Sketch

Import a McMaster Carr bolt (1/4-20, 7/16 inch bolt head) and sketch up a head pocket and bolt hole. Offset the bolt bits by .3mm to give some space, add a bunch of padding around the bolt to make it strong, then draw some circles.

Step 4: Extrude/Loft and Pretty it up

Extrude the top of the tripod, trim out the bolt head slot and bolt hole. Loft a few circles from the bottom down to a few slightly larger circles spaced outward from the small circles.

Chamfer all the edges that are printing on the bottom (in this case the top) to prevent any elephant footing and keep it feeling nice and smooth.

Bevel all of the edges that are printing on the top to make it feel smooth and to make it easier to insert hardware.
Bevel some inside edges to add a little extra strength (around the legs and at the "bottom" of the bolt head pocket).

Step 5: Worry

Worry that you aren't using the proper terms for what you did to design the part and that someone who learned how to use CAD software from a teacher might laugh at you or be confused by your inept descriptions of what you did. Also look up "chamfer" to make sure you are spelling it correctly and it is what you think it is because Chrome, for some reason, doesn't think chamfer is a correctly spelled word when it is capitalized, so you get a squiggly line in your documentation.

Rethink almost all of your decisions and spend a few minutes considering making all of the variations you came up with hypothetical people wanting to use if only you hadn't been short sighted and selfish to make just the one specific version you actually wanted.

Finally worry that a high paying job designing extremely basic 3D printable tripods might be slipping though your grasp because your design portfolio of tripods isn't thorough enough since you didn't make more than one of them and because you aren't using the right technical terms in your documentation that no one will ever read.

title: yacs one arm compact coin fidget toy

description.text:
Yet another coin fidget toy. This one is a compact one arm version. That means it is unbalanced. You can’t spin it on a fingertip, but instead you can get it to rotate by flicking your wrist, without touching the spinner itself.
This is sized for the standard 608 skate bearing, 22 mm × 7 mm.

There are two ready-made STLs there, for coins i had lying around:

  • four 1 euro cent coins
  • five 2 Indian rupee coins, 2007 version, nominally 27 mm ⌀, but slightly smaller IRL

This is slightly parametric. Whit a bit of work you can use your favourite coins, either local currencies, or parts of that little pile of foreign currency that travellers tend to collect. For that i have included the FreeCAD files. They include a spreadsheet called “sizes”. To get a new spinner, do this:

  • Download FreeCAD and get it running
  • Load the yacce_1_arm.fcstd FreeCAD file
  • In the tree view, double click on “Sizes”. You should see the spreadsheet
  • Measure your coin or look up its size (Wikipedia, search engine, &c.)
  • Put in the diameter and thickness in B6 and B7. Make sure to keep the = and mm.
  • Check that you have enough coins. The spreadsheet shows the number needed. Typically four, five for thin coins like the ₹2.
  • Change other values in the “B” column, like the whole spinner’s size, to taste.
  • Go back to the yacce_1_arm view
  • Check that the shown shape looks OK. There are view controls at the top
  • Check that in the tree view there are no exclamation marks as warnings
  • If there are problems, it’s easiest to close without saving and to try again. Change fewer values, and only by small amounts.
  • If the spinner looks good, select the last item, “spinner”. It should turn green in the main view.
  • Look for the dropdown in the tool bar and select “Mesh Design”
  • You should now have a “Meshes” menu. Select “Create mesh from shape …”
  • I have to select the “Standard” radio button. “Mefisto” produces empty meshes.
  • Click OK
  • There should be a “spinner (Meshed)” item in the tree view. Select it.
  • Click on the “Export a mesh to file” icon, enter a file name, select the file type (STL or OBJ) and click “OK”,
  • Et voilà, you’re done. You have finished your first FreeCAD lesson and can now go ahead and slice and print your customized spinner.

There is also some design history available at my github repo.

All my “yacs” spinners are related and started out with the same bearing ring.

description.text:
Remix of a dice rack for holding dice that was initially made by DanofLA. Holds a full set of polyhedral dice, just like his. Instead of holding two extra d20s though, I've added coin slots for the standard US sized coins (though the specific ones I use aren't all actual US coins.

Personally, I use a US Quarter, a Mexican Silver Dollar, one of those Angel Coins that float around (both sized the same as a US Quarter), a US Nickel, a US Penny, a US Dime, and a British Five Pence (sized the same as a US Dime).

The hexagonal towers have recessed holders for each type of dice, and most fit perfectly. The d20 slot is a little loose, intentionally since I'm always grabbing the thing above all others. The d6 slot was made a little too tight, admittedly on accident. I just sanded it down a little to fix it. The d6 does fit without sanding, but it has a pretty good grip on it. Should have made my model of the d6 a little bigger when I made the hole with it. :\

Doesn't include the same design that DanofLA has on theirs because I didn't want to spend the time to include it. If anyone wants to put them back, however, they're free to do so -- mine is published under the same Share-Alike license theirs is.

I printed the white one with Z-Marble from ziro3d, but I paused it in the middle because i had to move the printer slightly, and didn't want to mess up the print. Forgot that I printed it from Octoprint however, since I used the onboard pause button. Effectively canceling it. I had to make another slice of just the remaining layers, print that, and superglue it together.

The gold one was done with Hatchbox Gold PLA, and was done in one shot. Cleaned the print afterward with 70%, and then a light amount of 95% isopropyl alcohol. Gave it a nice semi-shine, although I wasn't actually should if it would do anything at all.

title: Adjustable-angle tablet-stand with print in place hinges

description.text:
This is my design for a print-as-one (print-in-place) hinged tablet stand that can be adjusted over a wide range of incline angles. I was looking around on thingiverse for something of this nature but could only find adjustable ones that need screws and nuts to assemble, or some other post-print assembly. I thought there must be a better way!

This will work straight off the print bed. Just peel away the brim and VERY CAREFULLY loosen the hinges and you're good to go. I've been using it with a large 9.7" Galaxy Tab S2 with a case on and it supports it nicely and feels very stable.

When you first unfold it, the inner two parts have to swing all the way round the outer base piece so that it brings the supports on to the top side of the base where the position notches are located. Then to put it away flat, just rotate all the way round to the back again.

There may well be a few improvements that could be made to the design, but I would welcome any comments and suggestions! At the moment, the supports are spaced a little too wide to use for my Samsung Galaxy S5 smartphone, so I have considered maybe a smaller version to accommodate phones as well. Not sure if the narrower design would become unstable for large tablets though.

UPDATE - 14/10/2017

I've now uploaded a narrower version that will support a smartphone. I haven't printed it myself yet, but the tolerances are all the same so it should work out fine. Let me know how you get on with it!

title: Extruder Quick Release Lever for Airtripper

description.text:
Here is a Quick Release Lever for the Airtripper Bowden Extruder.   
For filament release and tension on the Airtripper Bowden Extruder use this lever to make quick access easy. This is designed for using with a petrol hose for spring tension on the pressure bearing. But, can be adapted to use with springs if you make a pivot rod.   See Instructions for suggestions.

Directions:
  • Print one Quick Release Lever.
  • Clean and open the Lever pivot hole if required to fit onto your tubing.
    You want a slip fit. Not too tight - Not too loose.
  • Use a small amount of non-petroleum lubricant (for ABS) between the Lever and tubing. Any lubricant should work for PLA or Nylon.
  • Slip Lever onto the tubing between the two bolt holes.
  • Reinstall the tubing, bolts and your New Quick Release Lever.
  • Leave bolts loose.
  • Put Lever into closed position - See Pictures.
  • Tighten/Adjust Bolt tension on the filament.
  • Check Lever operation by Opening and Closing.
  • Open & Close, as required, when required. :-)
    • Springs?
    A suggestion to those using springs - Use a wood dowel or similar for a pivot rod. The pivot hole diameter of the Lever is approximately 13mm/.512". You will need bolts approximately 50mm/2" in length. These submissions were inspiration used as design aides.:
  • Quick Release Lever for 4mm bolt by jag (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7449)
  • Quick Release Lever for 4mm bolt w/Supports by Crypto (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:13370)
  • Quick Release Lever for wade by Simon Litwan (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:22830)

Something else entirely today.

This is a walker mech/suit of extremely powerful armour. Kitbashed from various little Blender greeblies I made for various other projects. Split into 6 separate parts to allow some customization.

The inspiration came from seeing Nick Carvers (kudos) concept art. I'm also building a custom SLA rig that I'll test using this model. Maybe, if it turns out well, a tabletop mech-based game? (Weta Workshop did something similar and it looks stunning, check it out!)

Notes:

Support - YES. Very much so. One component - the hatch guard rails - will probably fail to print due to it being ridiculously thin.

You'll have to be careful while removing the support structures. There are lots of them and there are bits that could easily be torn with them.

Citadel paints and washes are probably the easiest way of painting. Since those were the colours I had, the whole thing ended up sporting a danish flag, for reasons apparent to exactly noone.

General info

Same old, same old - Blender and LOTS of boolean operations. It's actually really effective - block out your design, bevel, chamfer, knife. Pepper with greeblies (boolean difference and union) Remarkably fun method, but can produce awful meshes. This was run through Netfabb Basic and sliced in S3D - looks OK.
This was produced in 5 hours total.

comments.text: Probably the first thing I found on Thingiverse that I wanted to print.. I tried it at 100% scaling before learning about how supports work.. After getting the swing of things on my Powerspec (Wanhao) Duplicator i3+, I thought I'd try printing this one again. I upped the size to 150% and that helped a bunch on the small parts.. It might be due to the .8mm nozzle my second hand printer came with, or my settings, but a few of the delicate structures were torn off.. Definitely an exercise in cautious support trimming! I'll be going back and changing out the hoses on the autocannons with black hair tie elastics. I think they'll give it the proper hose look. I found it printed best with the parts in their original orientation.. I printed a leg laying flat and.. ugh.. I did print two of the right arm (one mirrored) so it would look balanced.. I rotated an arm so that the barrel was horizontal to the print bed and it worked out pretty well.. That's, of course, the one I ripped out hoses accidentally so.. maybe I should have also printed that one the way it was.. Lots and lots of detail on this model! A set of good X-acto blades and probes is wise.. (Mine are the Harbor Freight kit, the blue one with all the blades and probes..) I'm having some trouble fitting the legs properly-- they have a conflict on the mounting stub, so I'm going to try trimming the stub so they fit a bit more snug. Same with the autocannon arms.. I broke the tabs off one side before realizing the arm was actually bottoming out on the stud.. I'll try drilling the hole a bit so it fits more flush.. Or, perhaps some hot glue.. Anyway, just a great design! Prints awesome in Hatchbox silver PLA.. Pics when I finish printing the base and get it mounted.. I don't even think I'll paint this one..

description.text:
​This design was created in order to fulfill the challenge of powering and controlling a small race car with the components of a small quadcopter. For this challenge, there were many constraints that lead to the design created. More details can be seen in the portfolio included.

The gears should be printed in a high strength/temp material, such as nylon. We ran out of time on this project to do so for all gears, and the wear on the non-nylon gears was very noticeable. The main body of the car was printed in Taulman t-glase PETT.

Assembly Guidelines:

The quadcopter utilized was a Hubsan X4. Disconnect all the motor wires from the control board. Depending on your preference, Solder extension cables to the motors. After passing the motor wires through the car body and reconnect them to the control board. The small gears can be press fit on the end of the motor shafts.

The wheels used were Maximum Velocity Speed Wheels. The large gears were slid onto the shaft and glued to the wheels. Because of time constraints we were not able to come up with a better way to secure the ends of the drive shafts. Please feel free to remix and improve this design!

title: E3D hot end mount for SeeMeCNC Rostock Max

description.text: This mount holds the E3D with Bowden fitting by clamping it between the two printed parts. These are screwed together, capturing the E3D between them. I did this for convenience since I constantly change out hot ends for testing, etc and wanted a simple mount with no loose parts. I simply disconnect two wiring connectors (fan and hot end/thermistor) and unscrew three thumbscrews and my hot end comes right off.
Nothing special to make it. I used 50% infill and 3 perimeters so it is strong. I used self-tapping 4-40 x 1/2" screws to assemble it. You could use machine screws and nuts too.

comments.text: I've had a few inquiries about my hot end setup. Basically, this is my "quick change" set up. I use hexagonal standoffs that are 1/2" long so I can easily adjust in 1/2" increments to accommodate different hot ends, a dial indicator, a drag engraver and a pen drawing tool holder. The larger bottom standoff is a female-female 3/8" hex. I had those in my shop, that's why they are larger than the 1/4" hexes above! The 1/4" hex standoffs are male-female. That way, they screw into the one already installed and the Acetal thumbscrews screw into their tops. To remove the hot end, I simply remove the 3 thumbscrews, disconnect the two connectors (one for fan and the other for hot end and thermistor) and remove the Bowden. Takes 30 seconds, tops.

title: Mini transparent printing test cube with embedded sphere

description.text:
This is a small solid cube with a spherical void inside it. This is useful to find good settings to obtain a truly transparent print on FDM printers before trying something larger and more advanced like cymon's skull dice.

I also provide a model with small drain holes if you want to print this on an SLA/DLP printer (where obtaining true transparency should be quite a bit easier than on an FDM printer).

The print shown is transparent ABS, but any transparent filament should work if you do the following things:

  • 100% infill, obviously
  • Print with a bit of over-extrusion (not too much, just enough to ensure air bubbles are pushed away from between the layers)
  • Print slowly
  • Print hot, with just enough cooling to keep the print from turning into one messy blob.
  • Printing in thin layers may help as well.

Natural PLA should also work to a certain degree, although its transparency is limited and will look milky for thicker objects. Polycarbonate, PETG, and Colorfabb HT are probably the best choices for a truly transparent print, although pretty good results can also be obtained with transparent ABS.

Printing on a glass bed will allow you to quickly see whether the print looks decent, because the bottom surface will be very smooth. If you can see the sphere through it, chances are that it will look good after polishing. If it looks milky or you can see air bubbles with a magnifying glass, there is no point in polishing it, you'll have to try again with different settings.

Notes:

Printed slowly, at about 22mm/s with minimal cooling.

Obviously, to obtain a transparent surface, you will need to sand and polish it to get rid of the layer boundaries. For transparent ABS, you can use acetone vapor smoothing, but from my tests, it doesn't produce as transparent a surface as simple mechanical polishing.
I sanded the surfaces with increasingly fine sandpaper. For the final polishing, I used plain ordinary paper, followed with a piece of semi-glossy magazine paper, which works surprisingly well (ideally, find something that has nothing printed on it, or you might be rubbing the ink into the plastic).

title: Iron Man ARC Reactor - slim and wearable

description.text:
Ironman ARC Reactor prop I made for Comic-con, only about 1.5cm thick when assembled so thin enough to be mounted in a t-shirt like I did.

See "ARC_-_All_Items_Example_only.stl" for reference, don't try and print this one. Do it in parts then assemble.

Fairly easy to assemble: The 3 ring supports fit into the backplate. On the ring supports sit the inner rings 4, 3, 2, 1 from the bottom to the top glued in place. Top ring then sits on top of the ring supports. The light ring opaque is where the light should emanate from, print in translucent and add LEDs for effect. I made the light ring from acrylic and sanded down to diffuse the lights. The 10 wire formers then sit on the light ring spaced evenly, wrapped in copper wire, then joined with thicker copper wire.

The backplate is in two variants, one with bigger holes to get larger wires or LEDs through.

Once complete you can fit into a piece of clothing, then use the clamp ring to glue it all in place.

All I did was disassemble it, extend the wires on the LEDs, mounted the circuit on the back, then extended the wires for the batteries and used an external pack. I loved ccbdav's idea for a wall target for putting on the edges of walls. I do flooring estimation, and often have to do very long laser shots. When I need to stop at a certain wall to make a corner I usually would have to do deductions with the Disto tool, and shoot to another wall.

I liked ccbdav's idea, but wanted mine hinged so I could rotate 90 degrees depening on which edge of the wall I would connecto to.

The magnet holes are for 12mm diameter 3mm thick magnets I got from Home Depot. They fit very snug but I still epoxied them into the holes.

I did not make this from scratch. I'm still learning Fusion 360. This started as Maker's Muze's file for demonstrating how to print live hinges. I then just pulled and rounded some corners to make it the size I wanted. Sadly the hinges did not print very well. It still holds it as it made little "divots" and works fine, but the hinge doesn't work as described. The "pin" of the hinge is too small. I plan on re-doing this as my skills in Fusion 360 get better.

This target fits great in my back pocket so I can carry it with me as I do my estimation.

Print this in either red or white for best reflectivity of the laser. Dark colors won't work very well. I used "Clay Red" $5 filament for the top and bottom layer, and white in the middle. 25% infill with 3 perimeters .20 layer height. 2 top and bottom solid layers. Solid red would have been fine, I just didn't have enough so I did the infill with white.

I was not able to screw it on the full length and twisted the holder. It was re-squared after 15 minutes in the oven (80°C).
I'll adapt the hollow part to give some play, and shorten the shaft a bit.

description.text:
I took the parts for the Walt Disney World Monorail Playset my wife and I got at our wedding for our Christmas trees (And has been a popular thing at christmas parties since), and made a rough sketch of it in Fusion 360. It should be accurate and ready to mate with the official, but I can't test due to printer being down. When that's resolved, I will post more and more elaborate parts. You just don't get enough track for the things, really. The rail is 100mm with a 10mm bore through for weight and also because it'd be awesome to print in Glow in the Dark PLA (Which I have a god-damn Kilo of) or translucent and run rope lights or LED strings through.

My secret goal is to build a scale model in my basement, like Rod Stewart did with 1930 Chicago, but with the Mecca of consumerism and family fun. I'm an irredemable nerd like that. Or, more realistically, build a playset for my daughter (Coming October 2017).
